title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare 1959 Colt frontier
postcontent: anomalous" .22 Magnum Colt Frontier Scout revolver. (If the word is unfamiliar, an anomaly is "something that deviates from what is standard, normal or expected.") The barrel is marked .22 Magnum, but has the flat muzzle that was typical of the .22 LR guns. Over many years of collecting the Frontier Scouts, I have owned two or three , I do not know why these revolvers exist. I do know that all the guns that I have seen in this configuration, fall into the 80000F-85000F serial number range (1959). According to Don Wilkerson's excellent book, "Colt Scouts, Peacemakers and New Frontiers in .22 Caliber" (Walsworth Publishing, 1993), the .22 Magnum chambering was introduced in the Frontier Scout line around serial number 48800F. If "transition" models existed, I would expect them to be in that number range, not 40,000 numbers later. However, Colt produced more than 50,000 Frontier Scouts in 1959 so some strange things could have happened in that period. Colt collectors have learned to "never say never". a very rare colt revolverNice older colt single action frontier scout revolver.22 magnum. Very nice smooth colt action, shiny bore, good lockup and timing. Not much wear , abit of light flecking that should clean up nice. Awesome plinker with a super light smooth action. Essentially a scaled down peacemaker in .22 'The New Frontier 22s made from 1970 until 1977 had barrels bored for the .22 Magnum even if shipped with only .22LR cylinders. The New Frontier 22s made from 1982 until the end of production had barrels bored for .22LR.If you have something I may be interested in please reply by email call or text REDACTEDTrade for a nice ak setup, mini14, 1911Revolvers in 357 44 45 41

title: For Sale:  1919A4 Lots of extras, 30-06, 8mm .308, 762x54r
postcontent: Up for sale is my longtime owned 1919a4. I have had this gun for some time but I have maybe only shot 200 rounds through it. That is the reason I am selling it, I do not live on shooting land, or have access to shoot this bad boy often enough to justify keeping it. Therefore, I would like to pass it on to another owner. I would advise only purchasing if you are skilled with firearms. These guns have adjustable head spacing and parts must be swapped out for caliber changes. But it is easy to pick up the operation. That said, I have collected over the years about all the accessories and spare parts you could ever want for one of these. This auction will include everything pictured. I have installed on it a crank fire system which will simulate FA firing speeds. I have caliber conversions for 8mm, 30-06, .308, and my favorite, 7.62x54r. You can shoot just about any surplus rifle round your heart desires through this 1919. Included also are all the spare parts pictured (and some more in the plastic bags), two semi auto bolts, one in 7.62x54, and one new one that has only been test shot in .308/30-06/8mm. Also included are two non-modified bolts in 30-06 and one in .308. An Israeli ground A6 style kit will also come with the 1919 which includes the carry handle, bipod, and stock set. Further, a BFA is included and I will add in 250 or so rounds of belted plastic .308 blanks. Lastly included is a multicaliber ammunition link loader. Works great and links up 20 metal links at a time. I will include about 100 metal links, plus the 250 linked on blanks and 3 cloth belts. Any other small 1919a4 parts I have will be included. I do not take selling this gun lightly, so I am going to try to sell as a set. I have listed it for what I have in it and what I believe it is all worth together. I would prefer buyer to pick up from Galveston Texas, If picked up I will include a very nice Sokolov Mount in for free, Otherwise buyer pays actual shipping. Gun is very heavy I may look to finding a crate to ship it in. Thanks again for looking. If shipping know your state laws. I am not responsible for knowing laws of other states. 1919 if shipped must ship to FFL but I can ship everything else to you.
